{{Infobox Artwork | image_file = Peter Paul Rubens - The Birth of the Milky Way, 1636-1637.jpg | image_size = 350px | title = The Origin of the Milky Way | artist = [[Peter Paul Rubens]] | year = {{circa|1637}} | medium = [[Oil on canvas]] | height_metric = 181 | width_metric = 244 | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | metric_unit = cm | imperial_unit = in | city = | museum = [[Museo del Prado]], Madrid, Spain }} '''''The Origin of the Milky Way''''', or '''''The Birth of the Milky Way''''',<ref name="prado">{{cite web | url =https://www.museodelprado.es/en/the-collection/online-gallery/on-line-gallery/obra/the-birth-of-the-milky-way/| title =The Birth of the Milky Way|publisher =[[Museo del Prado]]| accessdate =6 April 2014}}</ref> is a painting by the Flemish artist [[Peter Paul Rubens]], featuring the [[Milky Way (mythology)#Greek and Roman|Greco-Roman myth of the origin of the Milky Way]]. The painting depicts [[Hera]] ([[Juno (mythology)|Juno]]), spilling her [[breast milk]], the infant [[Heracles]] ([[Hercules]]) and [[Zeus]] ([[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]]) in the background, identifiable by his eagle and lightning bolts. Hera's face is modelled on Rubens' wife, [[Hélène Fourment]].<ref name="prado"/> The carriage is pulled by Hera's favourite animals, peacocks. Due to the dark background of the night sky the figures gain a greater sense of volume.
The image was a part of the commission from [[Philip IV of Spain]] to decorate [[Torre de la Parada]]. Rubens also painted other Greco-Roman mythological subjects, such as ''Hercules Fighting the Nemean Lion'' or ''[[Perseus Freeing Andromeda (Rubens)|Perseus Freeing Andromeda]]''.
